data.title: Madonna dropping new album Finally Enough Love with 50 No. 1 club hits
data.meta_description: Madonna's new album 'Finally Enough Love' will include 50 of her number-one hits, unreleased remixes, and rare versions of her classic songs. See the full track list here.
data.text:
Madonna is celebrating her record-breaking 40-year career with an epic new 50-song compilation album featuring all of her No. 1 club hits.

The pop superstar announced she will release Finally Enough Love: 50 Number Ones, the first collection in a planned retrospective package of projects highlighting her legendary discography, later this year.

On the LP's track list are some of the singer-songwriter's personal favorite remixes of her tunes, as well as rare and unreleased versions of time-tested songs and remastered takes on previously released material. The tracks span every era of Madonna's career, ranging from her debut single "Everybody" to mammoth hits like "Vogue," "Frozen," and "Hung Up."

The first official song from the album, "Into the Groove" (You Can Dance Remix Edit), is available now for the first time on digital platforms.

Several of Madonna's high-profile collaborations are also featured on the album's track list, including duets with Britney Spears ("Me Against the Music"), Justin Timberlake and Timbaland ("4 Minutes"), LMFAO ("Give Me All Your Luvin'" [Party Rock Remix]), Maluma ("Medellín"), and Nicki Minaj ("Bitch I'm Madonna").

Each remix on the album was newly remastered by Mike Dean, who worked extensively with Madonna on her two most recent albums of original material: 2015's Rebel Heart and 2019's Madame X.

In addition to the rerelease plan with Warner Music, Madonna is also currently working on bringing her life story to the big screen as the director of a feature-length biopic co-written by Oscar-winning Juno screenwriter Diablo Cody and Erin Wilson.

Universal Pictures and Amy Pascal are producing the title, for which EW previously confirmed actress Julia Fox met with Madonna to discuss potentially playing the entertainer's longtime friend Debi Mazar.

Madonna has revealed in the past that the movie will follow her "struggle as an artist trying to survive in a man's world as a woman." She described it as a "happy, sad, mad, crazy, good, bad, and ugly" tale touching on her rise to prominence in New York City, writing "Like a Prayer," filming Evita, and her connection with Jose Gutierez Xtravaganza and Luis Xtravaganza of New York City's Harlem ballroom scene, which played a pivotal role in the success of her 1990 smash "Vogue."

Ahead of the full Finally Enough Love: 50 Number Ones release on Aug. 19, a streamlined 16-track digital version of the album will drop June 24. "Into the Groove" (You Can Dance Remix Edit) is available alongside the album's pre-order now.
